The Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus, and asked him to show them a sign from heaven.
He replied, "In the evening you look at the sky. You say, 'The weather will be good. The sky is red."
In the morning you say, 'Today will be stormy. The sky is red and cloudy.' You know the meaning of what you see in the sky. But you cannot understand the signs of what is happening now.
A wicked and adulterous generation seeks after a sign! But no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah. And he left them and went away. The yeast of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
The pupils crossed to the other side of the lake. They had forgotten to bring bread.
"Make them," said Jesus. "Look at the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees."
The pupils spoke about this among themselves. They said, "He's saying this because we didn't bring any bread."
Jesus knew what they were saying. So he said to them, "Your faith is small! Why do you talk among yourselves about having no bread?"
Do you still understand? Do you not remember the five loaves for the five thousand? Do you not remember how many baskets full you gathered?
Do you not remember the seven loaves for the four thousand? How many baskets full of pieces did you gather?
How can you not understand? I was not talking to you about bread. But beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was not warning them about the leaven of bread, but about the teachings of the Pharisees and Sadducees. Peter said, "You are the Christ."
Jesus went to the region of Caesarea Philippi. There he asked his disciples, "Who do people say the Son of Man is?"
They answered, "Some say John the Baptist; others say Elijah; and others, Jeremiah or one of the prophets."
"But what about you?" he asked. "Who do you say I am?"
Simon Peter answered, "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God."
Jesus answered, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven.
This is what I tell you. You are Peter. On this rock I will build my church. The gates of hell will not be strong enough to destroy it.
I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven; whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.
Then Jesus warned his disciples not to tell anyone that he was the Christ. Jesus speaks of his upcoming death.
From that time Jesus began to explain to His disciples that He must go to Jerusalem, and suffer many things from the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and be raised up on the third day.
Peter took Jesus aside and began to rebuke him. "Never, Lord!" he said. "This shall never happen to you!"
Jesus turned and said to Peter, "Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me; for you are not setting your mind on the things of God, but on the things of man."
Then Jesus said to his disciples, "Whoever wants to follow me must deny themselves, take up their cross, and follow me.
"If he wants to save his life, he will lose it; but if he loses his life for my sake, he will find it."
What good is it for a man to gain the whole world, yet forfeit his soul? Or what can a man give in exchange for his soul?
Truly, the Son of Man is going to come in his Father's glory, with his angels, and then he will reward each person according to what they have done.
What I am telling you is the truth. Some of you standing here will not die before you see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom.
Jesus' appearance changes.
Six days later, Jesus took with him Peter and James and John, his brother, and led them up a high mountain by themselves.
There, before them, his appearance was transformed. His face shone like the sun. His clothes became white as light.
At that moment, Moses and Elijah appeared before them. Moses and Elijah were speaking with Jesus.
Peter said to him, "Lord, it is good for us to be here. If you wish, I will make three tents here, one for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."
While Peter was still speaking, a bright cloud enveloped them, and a voice from the cloud said, "This is my Son, whom I love; with him I am well pleased. Listen to him!"
When the disciple heard this, they were terrified and fell to the ground with their faces down.
But Jesus came and touched them, saying, "Arise, do not be afraid."
When they raised their eyes, they saw no one but Jesus.
They came down from the mountain. And as they were going down, Jesus instructed them, saying, "Tell no one what you have seen." He said to them, "Wait until the Son of Man has risen from the dead."
The disciples asked him, "Why do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?"
Jesus answered, "It is true, Elijah is coming to restore all things."
But I tell you, Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him, but did to him whatever they pleased. So also will the Son of Man suffer at their hands.
Then the disciples understood that Jesus was speaking to them about John the Baptist. Jesus heals a boy who had a demon.
As they approached the crowd, a man ran up to Jesus, fell on his knees before him,
"Oh Lord," he said, "have mercy on my son. He trembles severely and suffers greatly. He often falls into the fire or into the water.
I brought him to your disciples, but they could not heal him.
"You people are unbelievers and evil," Jesus said, "How much longer must I stay with you? How much longer must I put up with you? Bring the boy to me here."
Jesus commanded the demon to come out of the boy, and it did. He was healed instantly.
Then the disciples came to Jesus in private and asked, "Why could we not cast it out?"
He said, "Because your faith is so small. What I am telling you is the truth. If you have faith as small as a mustard seed, it is enough. You can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there,' and it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you."
